{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491673"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:57:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:57:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1016"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1016"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.05,0.5,0.17,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1016"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112343"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1016"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1016"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94391"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"9143"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5285"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5779"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6023"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9379"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14607"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33893"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112343"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department of a tertiary referral hospital with perianal pain and subjective fevers, on a background of three perianal abscesses over the past 12 months. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Upon questioning, he describes a long history of mild abdominal pain, intermittent diarrhoea and occasional mucous loss per rectum. On examination, he appears unwell with vital signs within normal limits. There is significant tenderness in the perianal region.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate investigation to perform prior to surgery?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Endorectal ultrasound","Tissue biopsy","Colonoscopy","CT scan","MRI"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven this patient\u0027s history of recurrent perianal abscesses and symptoms suggestive of inflammatory bowel disease, further investigation is warranted before surgical intervention. \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate immediate initial investigation in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMRI provides detailed imaging of the perianal region, allowing for identification of abscesses, fistulas, and other complex perianal pathology. It can also evaluate the surrounding pelvic structures and lower abdomen for signs of inflammatory bowel disease, particularly Crohn\u0027s disease. This information is crucial for guiding surgical management and determining the need for further workup before examination under anaesthesia. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndorectal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E can provide useful information about perianal abscesses and fistulas, but it is less comprehensive than MRI and may not adequately visualize deeper or more complex pathology. It is also less commonly used in Australia when MRI is available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETissue biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E would be valuable for establishing a diagnosis of inflammatory bowel disease, but it would typically be performed during surgical intervention or subsequent colonoscopy, not as a separate procedure beforehand.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is an important investigation for suspected inflammatory bowel disease, but it is not the most appropriate first step in this acute presentation. It would need to be performed based on the history provided to complete a full work-up for this patient. However, performing a colonoscopy immediately will not assist us in delineating the anatomy and the disease of the perianal region before an examination under anaesthesia. It will be more suitable as a follow-up investigation after the acute perianal issue has been addressed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan\u003C/strong\u003E can provide some information about perianal abscesses and surrounding structures, but it is less sensitive than MRI for soft tissue detail and fistula tracts. Additionally, CT exposes the patient to ionizing radiation, which is particularly concerning in a young patient who may require repeated imaging over time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, MRI is the preferred initial investigation as it provides comprehensive information about the perianal pathology and potential underlying inflammatory bowel disease, which will guide both immediate surgical management and long-term treatment planning.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["MRI is the preferred imaging modality for evaluating perianal abscesses and fistulas, especially when inflammatory bowel disease is suspected.","Recurrent perianal abscesses should raise suspicion for underlying inflammatory bowel disease, particularly Crohn\u0027s disease."],"references":["Lamb CA, Kennedy NA, Raine T, et al. British Society of Gastroenterology Consensus Guidelines on the Management of Inflammatory Bowel Disease in Adults. Gut [Internet]. 2019 Sep 27;68(Suppl 3):s1\u2013106. Available from: https://gut.bmj.com/content/68/Suppl_3/s1","Veauthier B, Hornecker JR. Crohn\u2019s Disease: Diagnosis and Management. American Family Physician [Internet]. 2018;98(11):661\u20139. Available from: https://www.aafp.org/afp/2018/1201/p661.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94391"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1016"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94391"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-30T12:14:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-30T12:15:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1016"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112343"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9143"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Anorectal abscess","synonyms":["Pilonidal abscess"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-15T12:13:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-18T09:07:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta